      {
        "id": 1,
        "lineId": 1,
        "beatId": 2,
        "bookId": null,
        "positionWithinLine": 0,
        "positionInBeat": 0,
        "title": "Exposition",
        "description": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "children": [
              {
                "text": "--- Add Your Details Above this Line ---"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "children": [
              {
                "text": "Beginning of Act 1:",
                "bold": true
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "children": [
              {
                "text": "The Exposition introduces the Protagonist, Central Characters, and the Ordinary World, and hooks readers into the story. There is no true action in this beat as it sets the scene and allows readers to see how things currently stand. In the end, it sets up the Inciting Incident."
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "bulleted-list",
            "children": [
              {
                "type": "list-item",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Introduce the Central Characters of the story, creating a Protagonist your readers can connect with and care about."
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "list-item",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Introduce the basic conflict of the story – the basic conflict is that which makes the Protagonist unhappy in their Ordinary World."
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "list-item",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Establish mood and atmosphere."
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "list-item",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Lead to the Inciting Incident."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "children": [
              {
                "text": "Example – Hamlet:",
                "bold": true
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "children": [
              {
                "text": "Opening of play, the introduction of Hamlet and most Central Characters. The King, Hamlet's father, has been killed. Denmark is under attack from the Norwegian Prince Fortinbras, Hamlet's family is in ruins, and his mother has remarried his uncle Claudius, whom Hamlet dislikes. Prince Hamlet is miserable, and the audience learns, possibly suicidal."
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "children": [
              {
                "text": "Breakdown:",
                "bold": true
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "bulleted-list",
            "children": [
              {
                "type": "list-item",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Act 1 makes up the first 25% of the story."
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "list-item",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "The Exposition should take approximately 15% of the story."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
